Rating: 2
To make this more flavorful, one should brown the lamb in small batches and reserve. Then saute the onions in a generous dollop of oil, stirring constantly until they turn golden brown (about 8-12 minutes). then add the garlic and ginger and stir-fry until they are fully fragrant. Instead of store-bought "curry powder" it's much better to use a teaspoon of ground cumin and a teaspoon of ground coriander, as the previous reviewer mentioned and stir for a minute. Then add some cayenne pepper to taste and and a half teaspoon of turmeric, being careful not to let the turmeric burn, and then add the tomatoes and browned lamb pieces. You could also add a little ground cinnamon and cloves before you add the tomatoes and lamb. If you don't really caramelize the onions and cook the spices well, the dish will be totally lacking in flavor. Another good trick is to keep the lamb bone from the butcher, brown it in the oven at 400 for an hour or so on a baking pan and add it with the lentils. Remove when you serve. Plain Basmati rice and a fresh coriander garnish would be beautiful. A wonderful Winter dish. Like chili, it's always better the next day, when the flavors have fully comingled. Make a triple batch and freeze it.

